","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/88251"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man was admitted to hospital three days ago for management of community acquired pneumonia. His medical history includes chronic liver disease, complicated by oesophageal varices. He has no known history of hypertension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis morning, he reports a mild headache, not relieved by paracetamol. He also has dull central chest pain, 7/10 in intensity, without radiation. He has never had this pain before. It is associated with dyspnoea but he reports no palpitations. He reports no abdominal pain nor back pain. He declined his morning medications this morning due to nausea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination his blood pressure is 190/110 mmHg, pulse rate 98/min regular, temperature 36.8\u00b0C, respiratory rate 16/min, and SpO2 98% on room air. Four hours ago, his blood pressure was 150/100 mmHg. Chest examination reveals fine crackles at both lung bases. His ECG shows T-wave inversions in the anterior leads.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the best descriptor for this clinical presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Severely elevated blood pressure without symptoms","Secondary hypertension","Hypertensive urgency","Hypertensive emergency","Portal hypertension"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with severely elevated blood pressure (190/110 mmHg) along with symptoms (headache, chest pain, dyspnoea) and evidence of acute end-organ damage (ECG changes suggesting myocardial ischaemia and crackles suggesting pulmonary oedema). According to current guidelines, the defining diagnostic feature of a \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypertensive emergency\u003C/strong\u003E is the presence of acute end-organ damage or dysfunction, which can occur at various blood pressure levels. The presence of chest pain with dyspnoea and ECG changes strongly suggests acute cardiac involvement, which constitutes end-organ damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESeverely elevated blood pressure without symptoms\u003C/strong\u003E is defined as blood pressure \u2265180/110 mmHg without symptoms and without evidence of end-organ damage or dysfunction. This patient clearly has symptoms and evidence of end-organ damage, making this classification inappropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypertensive urgency\u003C/strong\u003E is defined as severely elevated blood pressure (\u2265180/110 mmHg) with symptoms such as headache or dizziness, but without acute end-organ damage or dysfunction. While this patient does have symptoms, the presence of ECG changes and pulmonary crackles indicates acute end-organ damage, which excludes this classification.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESecondary hypertension\u003C/strong\u003E refers to elevated blood pressure with an identifiable cause. This term describes the etiology of chronic hypertension rather than the acuity or severity of the presentation. While this patient may have an underlying cause for his hypertension, the current presentation is best described by its acuity and severity rather than its etiology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPortal hypertension\u003C/strong\u003E refers to increased pressure in the portal venous system, typically due to liver disease. While this patient does have chronic liver disease with oesophageal varices (suggesting portal hypertension), this term does not describe his current presentation of severely elevated systemic blood pressure with evidence of end-organ damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of hypertensive emergency requires immediate blood pressure reduction (within minutes) using intravenous medications in a hospital setting (Emergency Department, ICU, or CCU). The goal is to reduce blood pressure quickly but without causing a precipitous fall, typically aiming to lower it by no more than 25% in the first 2 hours. This patient requires urgent evaluation for acute myocardial infarction and heart failure, along with appropriate management of his blood pressure.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Hypertensive emergency is defined by the presence of acute end-organ damage or dysfunction, not solely by blood pressure readings.","Chest pain with dyspnoea in the setting of severely elevated blood pressure requires urgent evaluation for acute end-organ damage.","Hypertensive urgency involves severely elevated blood pressure with symptoms but without acute end-organ damage or dysfunction."],"references":["Alley, W. and Schick, M., 2022. Hypertensive Emergency. [online] Ncbi.nlm.nih.gov. Available at: \u003Chttps://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470371/#:~:text=A%20hypertensive%20emergency%20is%20an,%2C%20aortic%20dissection%2C%20and%20eclampsia.\u003E","Paini A, Agguisti C, Bertacchini F, et al. Definitions and Epidemiological Aspects of Hypertensive Urgencies\nand Emergencies. High Blood Pressure \u0026 Cardiovascular Prevention (2018) 25:241\u2013244","Guideline for the diagnosis and management of hypertension in adults. 2022. Heart foundation. Available at https://www.heartfoundation.org.au/getmedia/c83511ab-835a-4fcf-96f5-88d770582ddc/PRO-167_Hypertension-guideline-2016_WEB.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72440"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11690"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72440","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/72440"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-02T19:21:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-02T19:27:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4305"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88251"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\